  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions can be traced through several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal anti-money laundering (AML) practices emerged in the 1920s during Prohibition era in the United States\n- Criminals sought ways to legitimize proceeds from illegal activities like bootlegging\n\n2. Initial Legislative Frameworks:\n- Bank Secrecy Act of 1970 (United States) was the first major legislative effort to combat money laundering\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs introduced international cooperation\n- Recommended criminalizing money laundering related to drug trafficking\n- Encouraged international information sharing and asset seizure\n\n4. Global Regulatory Expansion:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed comprehensive international standards for combating money laundering\n- Created 40 recommendations for national legal and regulatory systems\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded money laundering prohibitions\n- Increased reporting requirements\n- Enhanced international cooperation against terrorist financing\n\n6. Ongoing Evolution:\n- Continual adaptation to emerging financial technologies\n- Increased focus on cryptocurrency and digital transactions",
